–1285":"1209–1285","1224–Female":"1224–Deceased","1248–1285":"1248–1285","–Male":"Deceased","1168–Female":"1168–Deceased","1248":"1248","1224":"1224","1245":"1245","1168":"1168","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1209":"1209","Ci Tredegyr, Monmouthshire, Wales l-sant, Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llanwinio, Carmarthenshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: from a short form of the personal name <i>Adelhard</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, composed of the elements <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>hard</i> ‘bold, hardy’. Compare   Ale   and   Alma   4.","Swedish: variant of   Ahl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ale","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Carlos Enrique, Cesar, Jose, Maria De Jesus.","Spanish (Andalusia; <b>Alé</b>): unexplained.","Italian (Sicily; <b>Alé</b>): probably a variant of   Aleo  ."]}]},{"name":"Llwelyn","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i> (the name of a god;  see  Lleu  ); the second is a name-forming element found also in names such as <i>Cunobelinus</i> (<i>Cymbeline</i>). The name was borne by  Llywelyn ap Iorwerth  (  1173–1240 ) and his grandson Llywelyn ap Gruffydd (  d. 1282 ), Welsh princes who for a time united their countrymen in North Wales and led opposition to the power of the Norman barons in South Wales and the Marches."],"variants":[{"name":"Llywellyn","meanings":["Traditional: altered form (influenced by <i>llew</i> ‘lion’) of <i>Llywelyn</i>, an ancient name of uncertain derivation. It probably goes back to the Old Celtic name <i>Lugobelinos</i>, the first element of which is <i>Lugu-</i>